TY  - JOUR
AU  - Neumann, Robert
AU  - Voetmann, Torben
T1  - Demand Curves for European Stocks Slope Down Too
PY  - 2003
Y1  - 2003/01/01
DO  - 10.1023/B:EUFI.0000022150.48956.84
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 7
IS  - 3
SP  - 437
EP  - 457
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  -  The 2000 implementation of float-capitalization index weights in the Dow Jones STOXX SM indices changed the demand for large European stocks. In this paper, we test for imperfect-substitution and price-pressure effects due to the change in the demand for stocks. Our results show that we cannot reject complete reversal after eight weeks of abnormal trading volume for companies with both decreased or increased index weights. This result is consistent with the existence of downward sloping demand curves for stocks. Contrary to the fundamental assumption of perfectly elastic demand curves in asset pricing theories, our findings suggest that a price pressure effect is not a plausible explanation. JEL classification codes: G11; G14 
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1023/B:EUFI.0000022150.48956.84
ER  - 



